{"title_page": "List of Colorado Buffaloes head football coaches", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\nThe [[Colorado Buffaloes football]] program represents the [[University of Colorado Boulder]] in the [[Pac-12 Conference]] South Division of the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]]. The team has had 25&nbsp;head coaches since it started playing organized football in 1890. The university adopted the nickname ''Buffaloes'' in 1934 after previously being known as the ''Silver and Gold'', ''Silver Helmets'', ''Yellow Jackets'', ''Hornets'', ''Arapahoes'', ''Big Horns'', ''Grizzlies'' and ''Frontiersmen''.<ref name=\"Nicknames\"/> Colorado played without a head coach during their first four years. The team first joined a conference in 1893 when they became a member of the Colorado Football Association. They joined the Colorado Faculty Athletic Conference in 1909, immediately followed by the [[Rocky Mountain Athletic Conference]] in 1910. Before the 1938 season, Colorado joined the [[Mountain States Conference|Mountain States (Skyline) Conference]]. They joined the Big Seven Conference in 1948, which was renamed the [[Big Eight Conference]] in 1958 when Oklahoma State joined/rejoined the Conference.<ref name=\"Big_7_8\"/> The Buffaloes became a charter member of the Big 12 in 1996 when the Big Eight disbanded.<ref name=\"Big12Hist\"/> The Buffaloes have played in 1,139&nbsp;games during their 120&nbsp;seasons. In those seasons, nine coaches have led Colorado to postseason [[bowl game]]s: [[Bunny Oakes]], [[Dallas Ward]], [[William E. Davis|Bud Davis]], [[Eddie Crowder]], [[Bill Mallory]], [[Bill McCartney]], [[Rick Neuheisel]], [[Gary Barnett]], and [[Dan Hawkins (American football)|Dan Hawkins]]. Nine coaches have won [[athletic conference|conference]] championships with the Buffaloes: [[Fred Folsom]], [[Myron E. Witham|Myron Witham]], [[Bill Saunders|William Saunders]], Oakes, [[James J. Yeager|Jim Yeager]], [[Sonny Grandelius]], Mallory, McCartney, and Barnett.\n\nMcCartney is the all-time leader in games coached, with 153, and total wins, with 93. Folsom had the longest tenure as head coach, remaining in the position for 15&nbsp;seasons. [[Harry Heller]] and [[Willis Kienholz|Willis Keinholtz]] are tied for the highest overall [[winning percentage]]. Each served a single season and won eight of his nine games for a winning percentage of .889. Of coaches who served more than one season, Folsom leads with a .765 winning percentage. [[Jon Embree]] is, in terms of overall winning percentage, the worst coach the Buffaloes have had with a .160 winning percentage. Former Colorado head coach Bill McCartney was inducted into the [[College Football Hall of Fame]] in 2013 and is the only CU coach to have won several national coach of the year honors, with all of them coming in 1989. Barnett won conference coach of the year honors in 2001 and 2004. [[Mike MacIntyre]] was hired on December 10, 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.buffzone.com/cu-news/ci_22161228/cu-buffs-hire-mike-macintyre-lead-football-program |title=Football: CU Buffs hire San Jose State's Mike MacIntyre to lead football program |date=2012-12-10 |author=Kyle Ringo |accessdate=2012-12-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121213041204/http://www.buffzone.com/cu-news/ci_22161228/cu-buffs-hire-mike-macintyre-lead-football-program |archive-date=2012-12-13 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Key==\n{{List of college football program head coaches key}}\n\n==Coaches==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! No.\n! Name\n! Term\n! GC\n! OW\n! OL\n! OT\n! O%\n! CW\n! CL\n! CT\n! C%\n! PW\n! PL\n! CCs\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Awards\n\n|-\n| 1\n| {{Sortname|Harry|Heller}}\n| {{sort|1894|1894}}\n| 9\n| 8\n| 1\n| {{ntsh|0.1}}0\n| {{Winning percentage|8|1}}\n| {{nts|5}}\n| {{ntsh|0.1}}0\n| {{ntsh|0.1}}0\n| {{Winning percentage|5|0}}\n| {{ntsh|0}}\u2014\n| {{ntsh|0}}\u2014\n| {{ntsh|0}}\u2014\n| {{ntsh|0}}\u2014\n\n|-\n| 2\n| {{Sortname|Fred|Folsom}}\n| {{sort|1895|1895\u20131899, 1901\u20131902, 1908\u20131915}}{{#tag:ref|Folsom became Colorado's head coach before the second game of the 1895 season.  The team had no head coach in the season opener, a 42&ndash;0 victory over Denver Manual High School.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cubuffs.com/fls/600/football/2010_Info_Guide/coaching_records_pg129.pdf?DB_OEM_ID=600 |title=2010 Colorado Football Information Guide & Record Book |publisher=[[Colorado Buffaloes|University of Colorado Buffaloes]] |page=129 |accessdate=November 22, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120316071818/http://www.cubuffs.com/fls/600/football/2010_Info_Guide/coaching_records_pg129.pdf?DB_OEM_ID=600 |archivedate=March 16, 2012 }}</ref>|group=\"A\"}}\n| 103\n| 77\n| 23\n| {{nts|2}}\n| {{Winning percentage|77|23|2}}\n| {{nts|37}}\n| {{nts|13}}\n| {{nts|1}}\n| {{Winning percentage|37|13|1}}\n| {{ntsh|0}}\u2014\n| {{ntsh|0}}\u2014\n| {{nts|10}}\n| {{ntsh|0}}\u2014\n\n|-\n| 3\n| {{Sortname|T. C.|Mortimer|T. W. Mortimer}}\n| {{sort|1900|1900}}\n| 10\n| 6\n| 4\n| {{ntsh|0.1}}0\n| {{Winning percentage|6|4}}\n| {{nts|1}}\n| {{nts|2}}\n| {{ntsh|0.1}}0\n| {{Winning percentage|1|2}}\n| {{ntsh|0}}\u2014\n| {{ntsh|0}}\u2014\n| {{ntsh|0}}\u2014\n| {{ntsh|0}}\u2014\n\n|-\n| 4\n| {{Sortname|Dave|Cropp}}\n| {{sort|1903|1903\u20131904}}\n| 19\n| 14\n| 4\n| {{nts|1}}\n| {{Winning percentage|14|4|1}}\n| {{nts|7}}\n| {{nts|1}}\n| {{ntsh|0.1}}0\n| {{Winning percentage|7|1}}\n| {{ntsh|0}}\u2014\n| {{ntsh|0}}\u2014\n| {{ntsh|0}}\u2014\n| {{ntsh|0}}\u2014\n\n|-\n| 5\n| {{Sortname|Willis|Keinholtz|Willis Kienholz}}\n| {{sort|1905|1905}}\n| 9\n| 8\n| 1\n| {{ntsh|0.1}}0\n| {{Winning percentage|8|1}}\n| {{ntsh|0}}\u2014\n| {{ntsh|0}}\u2014\n| {{ntsh|0}}\u2014\n| {{ntsh|0}}\u2014\n| {{ntsh|0}}\u2014\n| {{ntsh|0}}\u2014\n| {{ntsh|0}}\u2014\n| {{ntsh|0}}\u2014\n\n|-\n| 6\n| {{Sortname|Frank|Castleman}}\n| {{sort|1906|1906\u20131907}}\n| 17\n| 7\n| 6\n| {{nts|4}}\n| {{Win